<TEXT>
the surrender of sikh extremists in 
their sacred golden temple did not end the war of terror through 
which they hope to create a nation called khalistan the land of 
the pure 
during the 10 days sikh gunmen and their sympathizers spent 
inside the temple complex surrounded by about 2800 policemen and 
soldiers their comrades killed 133 people in the holy city of 
amritsar and other parts of punjab state 
twentyfive more people were reported killed thursday the day 
after the surrender at the temple in amritsar they included two 
hindu priests and a sikh holy man 
it is from punjab a rich northern agricultural state that the 
radicals would create khalistan it is the only state where sikhs 
who make up only 2 percent of indias 800 million people are in 
the majority 
julio f ribeiro former police chief of punjab and now security 
adviser to the state government was asked if the surrender 
indicated an end to terrorism he replied no far from it 
bomb disposal squads searched for hidden explosives thursday in 
the 400yearold golden temple the holiest shrine of sikhism 
police said four more bodies were found inside bringing the death 
toll of the siege to 46 
a committee of sikh elders that manages the temple conferred 
about preparations to reopen the golddomed shrine 
sikh extremists began fighting for a separate homeland six years 
ago accusing the hindudominated federal government of 
discrimination and of hampering economic development in punjab 
thousands of people have been killed since then 
prime minister rajiv gandhi signed a peace agreement with 
moderate sikhs in 1985 but it fell apart within a year 
the sikh extremists initially blamed for scattered killings 
have attacked loaded buses sleeping villagers and congested 
markets in recent years at least 1088 people have been killed in 
punjab so far this year compared to 1032 for all 1987 
most victims are hindus but an increasing number of sikh 
moderates are being slain 
police estimate the radicals have more than 3000 men under 
arms with increasingly sophisticated weapons 
the greatest fear of gandhis government is that the separatist 
movement will become a fullscale civil war and encourage 
insurgencies among other minorities 
so far the terrorists are a small section of the 
population one official said privately we want to keep it 
that way 
support for the extremists within the sikh community may be 
waning after an army raid on the golden temple complex in 1984 
angry sikhs held rallies 
but hardly any sikhs objected publicly to the siege of the 
temple that ended wednesday and a gathering of sikh temple 
managers in new delhi passed a resolution wednesday praising the 
governments rescue of the shrine 
prime minister indira gandhi ordered the 1984 raid to drive out 
extremists taking shelter in the temple about 1200 people were 
killed two of mrs gandhis sikh guards assassinated her five 
months later 
prominent sikhs generally believe the violence will continue 
until the government of rajiv gandhi indiras son and successor 
reaches a political compromise with the militants 
kushwant singh a respected sikh writer urged the government 
recently to abandon its practice of searching for a single moderate 
sikh to lead peace efforts 
what we have to find is not a person or persons to lead the 
punjab but a way to set out principles of conduct and stick to 
them no matter what the immediate consequences he wrote in the 
hindustan times newspaper 
he advocated release of hundreds of sikhs detained without 
trial prosecution of hindu politicians and others accused of 
instigating the antisikh riots in 1984 and new investment to 
stimulate punjabs faltering economy 
gandhis 1985 accord with moderates called for settlement of 
land and water disputes between punjab and neighboring haryana 
state investigation of the 1984 riots and speedy handling of 
arrest and detention cases 
he put punjab under federal rule in may 1987 after the 
agreement had failed but in march of this year returned to a 
softer approach and ordered the release from prison of militant 
sikh high priest jasbir singh rode 
rode was arrested last week trying to march on the temple to end 
the police siege 
</TEXT>
