the former president of a maryland cocacola 
bottler and the chairman of the company that once owned a rival 
pepsicola bottling operation have been convicted of price fixing 
by a federal jury 
sentencing for james j harford former president of 
midatlantic cocacola bottling co of silver spring md and 
morton m lapides chairman of the board of allegheny beverage 
corp of cheverly md has not been set the two face a maximum of 
three years in prison 
they were convicted thursday of conspiring to set the wholesale 
price of their products between february 1983 and the fall of 1985 
allegheny beverage was the parent company of allegheny pepsicola 
bottling co 
in the sixweek trial prosecutors sought to show that both 
companies enjoyed higher profits because of the artifical inflation 
of their wholesale prices they provided no estimate of cost to the 
consumer 
they didnt want a price war and gave a green light to 
pricefixing said assistant us attorney david jordan of the 
defendants 
a third executive indicted odis r allen vice president of 
midatlantic pleaded guilty march 22 to one count of price fixing 
prosecutors said allen met numerous times with other softdrink 
executives to scheme about boosting wholesale prices of both coke 
and pepsi 
the defense contended that harford and lapides were unaware of 
what was happening and were hostile competitors who had fought 
each other in court and in the marketplace 
the indictments came out of a wideranging justice department 
probe of the soft drink industry 
in march allegheny and midatlantic agreed to refund 45000 to 
state and local governments for cola bought by school districts 
during the time of the alleged price fixing 
</TEXT>
