<TEXT>
nasa still hopes to launch the first 
postchallenger space shuttle in august but the agency is 
uncertain whether it can meet a goal of nine flights next year the 
head of the shuttle program says 
the reason for the doubt is the explosion that destroyed the 
pacific engineering and production co plant in henderson nev on 
may 4 the explosion eliminated the source of half the nations 
supply of a chemical used for the shuttle boosters and some other 
rockets 
a second plant in henderson owned by kerrmcgee has shut down 
for inspections to see that it is safe pacific engineering and 
kerrmcgee were the only american companies manufacturing ammonium 
perchlorate an oxidizer the oxidizer makes sure the solid rocket 
fuel burns evenly 
richard truly associate administrator for space flight of the 
national aeronautics and space administration said thursday that 
rocketmaker morton thiokol has enough ammonium perchlorate on hand 
for four flights and there is enough on hand for a fifth rocket 
set the titan 4 also uses ammonium perchlorate 
the chemical in the form of white crystals is taken by rail 
car to morton thiokols plant in utah mixed there and poured into 
the segments that make the booster rockets 
the issue will first come up in 1989 but were not certain 
there is going to be an impact in 1989 until we get together with 
the dod department of defense to match requirements and 
availability truly said 
he said nasa and the air force will have to decide how to divide 
up the output of kerrmcgee 
he said the first postchallenger flight still is on schedule 
for launch in late august he insisted the agency had not set a 
firm date but is working toward a target of aug 22 
pacific engineering said the explosion which killed two people 
and injured 326 was caused by a natural gas leak pacific 
engineering and kerrmcgee each produced 30 million pounds per year 
of ammonium perchlorate 
morton thiokol spokesman rocky raab said the company hasnt 
ruled out buying ammonium perchlorate from foreign firms but added 
the rest of the world supply is pretty meager ive seen 
estimates of worldwide production of nine million pounds a year 
a pair of shuttle booster rockets uses 15 million pounds of 
ammonium perchlorate per flight 
