president reagans spokesman says the 
administration is wary of giving military personnel 
drugtrafficking arrest powers because you cross an enormous 
bridge when you move them to an enforcement role 
spokesman marlin fitzwater on thursday did not directly oppose a 
bill passed overwhelmingly by the senate to allow the navy to make 
arrests on the high seas but he said the administration is very 
cautious in that area 
i think the american people would want us to be cautious 
fitzwater said but that does not diminish the idea that there 
are expanded roles for the military 
defense secretary frank c carlucci and adm william crowe 
chairman of the joint chiefs of staff oppose attempts by congress 
to substantially change a military role which now consists 
primarily of surveillance 
fitzwater was asked about a change reagan made in a speech 
wednesday on the subject the prepared remarks had called for 
reagan to say he had directed carlucci to search for creative 
solutions on how we can better use military resources and 
technologies to detect and interdict drugs coming into this 
country 
but when he actually delivered the speech reagan changed that 
line to say he wanted carlucci to find better ways for the military 
to detect drugs and support civil law enforcement agencies in 
interdiction 
asked about the significance of the change fitzwater said 
there is a very great concern about what it means to make law 
enforcement officers out of the military 
you cross an enormous bridge when you move them from providing 
military support and surveillance and physical interdiction efforts 
to making arrests and legal judgments and so forth he said 
as i think it was dan pentagon spokesman dan howard the 
other day said the first time an f15 shoots down a dentist 
because his airplane radio doesnt work you begin to understand 
the dimensions of the problem 
the chamber last friday voted 836 for an amendment outlining a 
wideranging antidrug role for the military 
the proposal calls for more surveillance by air force and navy 
planes increased antidrug activity by the national guard and more 
pentagon helicopters for the coast guard and customs service 
the most controversial provision would require navy vessels to 
track suspected drug boats and would allow navy officers to arrest 
suspected drug traffickers in international waters the officers 
would be temporarily deputized by coast guard officers who 
would be aboard for that purpose 
fitzwater however likened the drug trade to a 30foot tidal 
wave hitting a 25foot wall and said the fact is that 
interdiction is never going to solve the problem without cutting 
the demand 
