a college business group says 50 of the 
wealthiest american universities lost 131 percent of their 
endowments in the last quarter of 1987 as a result of the stock 
market crash 
by comparison common stocks overall dropped 226 percent during 
the final three months of 1987 as measured by the standard and 
poors 500 the national association of college and university 
business officers said thursday 
the group which has tracked endowments since 1974 said the 
downturn came after an excellent year for the campus funds 
including a gain of nearly 25 percent in the stock market during 
the 12 months that ended on june 30 1987 
the typical campus had little more than half its endowment 
invested in stocks the overall return on their holdings in the 
198687 academic year was 139 percent the business officers said 
in arriving at the 139 percent figure the association used 
data supplied by 296 colleges and universities with endowments 
ranging from 15 million for indiana university of pennsylvania to 
4 billion for harvard 
the market value of the endowments of all 296 institutions was 
479 billion at midyear the report did not provide a cumulative 
figure for after the crash 
there are more than 3000 colleges and universities in the 
united states the association study covers most of those with 
endowments of 1 million or more 
while the group normally reports trends from july of one year 
through june of the next it commissioned a special analysis by 
cambridge associates on the impact of the oct 19 stock market 
crash when the dow jones industrial average of 30 industrial 
stocks fell 508 points 
the october 1987 stock market tumble caused 50 college and 
university endowments of 100 million or more to fall an average of 
131 percent in the fourth quarter of the calendar year said the 
study reported in the may issue of business officer an 
association magazine 
after the market meltdown those 50 universities engaged in 
a modest repositioning it said the 50 were not named and no 
figures were given on where their endowments stood after the tumble 
between sept 30 and dec 31 their asset allocations went from 
63 percent to 57 percent stocks from 27 percent to 32 percent 
bonds and from 10 percent to 11 percent cash 
at midyear among all 296 colleges and universities the 
average investment pool was composed of 542 percent stocks 294 
percent bonds 127 percent cash and equivalents 19 percent real 
estate and 18 percent other assets 
