<TEXT>
the house is expected to act quickly on 
legislation requiring lenders to make full disclosure of what one 
of the sponsors calls the potential pitfalls of home equity 
loans 
rep charles schumer dny a major sponsor of the bill said 
he expected it to become law rapidly after clearing the house 
banking committee on thursday by a unanimous voice vote he noted 
the senate has already approved a similar but less stringent 
measure 
home equity loans can be like a loaded pistol said schumer 
consumers need to beware or they can blow up in their face 
the legislation requires lenders to make full disclosure on home 
equity loan accounts so that new applicants can know exactly what 
it is they are applying for 
lenders would have to provide information on the annual interest 
percentage rate any fees associated with the loan a series of 
warnings about the risks involved and a description of repayment 
options 
with the passage of the bill the committee is taking the 
mystery out of the home equity loans and hopefully providing 
consumers with a guide to the potential pitfalls of home equity 
loans he said 
rep frank annunzio dill chairman of the house banking 
consumer affairs subcommittee which handled the bill echoed the 
sentiments of schumer and other proponents of the legislation 
this legislation enables consumers to know that home equity 
loans have risks as well as benefits annunzio said this 
legislation will assure that they receive at the time of 
application all the information necessary to make an informed 
decision whether to apply for such a loan 
in addition it will strictly limit areas which were 
susceptible to abuse by the unilateral action of creditors 
the bill also provides for other consumer protections 
a prohibition on a creditor unilaterally changing the terms of 
the loan contract 
requiring the use of publicly available indexes outside the 
control of the lender when the rate of interest varies 
restrictions on the lender from calling in the loan before the 
term of the loan 
a right to obtain a refund of application fees if the lender 
changes the terms after an application is submitted but before the 
account is opened 
the committees action was lauded by consumer organizations but 
the american bankers association said the disclosure and 
advertising provisions are impractical they will result in an 
unnecessary overload of information for consumers and they will 
severely limit the creditors ability to design informative 
advertisements 
home equity loans a line of credit available to borrowers who 
provide their homes as collateral have grown more popular in 
recent years especially since interest on them is tax deductible 
in most cases 
consumer groups report that home equity lending doubled between 
1986 and 1987 from 40 billion to 80 billion 
