<TEXT>
nearly 1000 physicans in pennsylvania and 
new jersey received kickbacks as part of a medicare fraud scheme 
involving a medical laboratory company say federal officials 
it is believed to be the nations largest medicare fraud case in 
terms of the number of doctors involved said assistant us 
attorney james g sheehan 
the 987 doctors were paid a 50 kickback by medical diagnostic 
services inc for each patient referred to the company for a blood 
circulation test sheehan said 
the us attorneys office has mailed letters to 382 of the 
doctors over the last two days requesting they pay the government 
three times the amount they allegedly received in order to avoid 
civil action and expulsion from the medicare program sheehan said 
the 382 doctors received a total of 200000 in fees or an 
average of about 523 most of them were calling to offer to settle 
the claims sheehan said 
many of the remaining doctors received less than 150 and are 
not expected to be pursued in the case the philadelphia inquirer 
reported today citing unidentified federal sources fewer than 100 
physicians received more than 5000 apiece in fees and are 
expected to be prosecuted individually the newspaper said 
medical diagnostic services billed medicare 400 to 1000 per 
patient contending that it had performed a sophisticated test when 
in fact it had conducted only a simple routine test sheehan said 
this is a classic medicare ripoff one investigator 
familiar with the case which is being investigated by the 
inspector generals office of the department of health and human 
services the fbi and the us attorneys office in philadelphia 
told the inquirer 
between august 1982 and february 1985 medical diagnostic 
services operating under four different corporate names in new 
jersey and pennsylvania billed medicare for about 45 million 
the newspaper said 
