<TEXT>
thieves smashed a window at the 
municipal museum today and made off with three 19thcentury 
paintings worth up to 52 million including works by vincent van 
gogh and paul cezanne 
museum officials said it was the largest art theft in modern 
dutch history 
stolen were carnations an 1888 work by van gogh the 
house of maitre billaud in nevers by dutch painter johan 
jongkind from 1874 and bottle with apples an 1894 still life 
by cezanne the french impressionist 
museum director wim beeren estimated their combined value at 52 
million but the christies auction firm in london set their worth 
at 11 million 
the theft at the downtown museum also known as the stedelijk 
museum was discovered after 5 am when someone broke a window in 
the building and triggered an alarm 
museum spokesman maarten bertheux said no one was inside at the 
time he said the museums estimated 3000 works are protected only 
by an electronic alarm system when the museum is closed 
roundtheclock surveillance by security personnel was abolished 
as an economy measure in 1975 beeren said this is a terrible 
loss of prestige for museum security he told reporters the 
stolen paintings were not insured 
the museum famed for its collection of works by 19th and 
20thcentury masters is a threestory building with large windows 
on the street level the thieves entered through one of those 
windows that faces a secluded treeshrouded area officials said 
they walked through five galleries before reaching the room 
where the stolen paintings were on display with two other van gogh 
works according to deputy director rini dippel 
ms dippel speculated that the thieves left the other two van 
gogh paintings the rocking chair and the diggers because 
they were substantially larger than carnations which measures 
184 by 15 inches 
there were conflicting accounts on how the theft was discovered 
police spokeswoman heleen van der weijden police arrived on the 
scene after the alarm sounded and entered the museum but failed to 
notice the theft she said the theft was discovered an hour later 
by a private security guard 
bertheux said museum staffers and police discovered the theft 
about 20 minutes after the alarm sounded 
recent tests of the alarm system showed it took only three 
minutes for police and guards to get there beeren said he could 
give no explanation for the delay 
mrs van der weijden said interpol and customs services around 
the world were alerted 
