<TEXT>
hundreds of seals in danish waters 
are dying of pneumonia and the mysterious epidemic could spread to 
marine mammals in the baltic sea a biologist said friday 
more than 200 harp seals are known to have died in recent weeks 
on the island of anholt in kattegat strait between denmark and 
sweden said biologist paul mortensen 
he said the areas entire 1988 generation of seals was lost 
because their sick mothers aborted 
dying or dead seals also have been found beached on the islands 
of laesoe hesseloe and as far south as the port city of 
helsingoer giving rise to fears that the infection might spead he 
said 
he said the virus spreads by direct contact between adult seals 
as they lie close together on land adding that it resembles an 
influenza that struck hundreds of seals on the canadian and us 
eastern coasts in 1980 
another expert knud pedersen of the state veterinary serum 
institute said he suspected a herpeslike virus similar to one 
blamed for seal deaths of seals off the netherlands a few years ago 
experts from several government agencies met in copenhagen to 
discuss the crisis they agreed that more seals will die in the 
next few months as the epidemic spreads 
the harp seal was near extinction in 1975 when it was declared 
a protected species an estimated 5000 of the mammals inhabit 
danish waters breeding 500 to 1000 pups a year 
