<TEXT>
president reagan signed federal legislation 
thursday approving the appalachian states lowlevel radioactive 
waste compact but warned the compact commission against attempting 
to enforce federal laws 
in a statement announcing his signature reagan said more than 
three quarters of the states have now entered compacts on lowlevel 
radioactive waste 
he said such actions underscore this nations commitment to 
take those actions needed to ensure the future availability of 
nuclear power as an energy supply option for this country 
reagan objected however to a provision of the bill assigning 
federal law enforcement responsibility to the commission without 
requiring that commissioners be appointed consistently with the 
appointments clause of the constitution 
any effort by the commission to enforce federal regulations 
would contravene the constitution the president said 
while i hope that no such effort would occur i expect the 
nuclear regulatory commission to take note of and report to the 
attorney general on any such actions of the commission in this 
area 
under the compact which includes pennsylvania west virginia 
delaware and maryland the four states are required to ensure that 
there is a regional facility sufficient to dispose of the regions 
lowlevel waste and that each state has equal access to it 
the commission created under the compact is empowered to set 
regulations on waste disposal and to impose fines or other 
penalties for violations 
during consideration of the bill the justice department told 
congress that this part of the bill was unconstitutional because it 
applied to federal as well as state regulations 
the department said enforcing federal regulations pursuant to a 
congressionally approved interstate compact constitutes the 
exercise of significant authority pursuant to the laws of the 
united states 
in order to do this the department said the compact members 
would have to be appointed by the president or by other federal 
authorities designated by congress as provided in the constitution 
instead the commission members are appointed by the states 
in a letter to the senate judiciary committee the governors of 
the compact states said they did not believe a constitutional issue 
would arise because the compact was never intended to apply to 
activities over which the federal government has exclusive 
jurisdiction 
</TEXT>
