state officials said friday they found no 
evidence that rooms in a welfare hotel had been divided into tiny 
cubicles and said it was acceptable for two families to share a 
bathroom 
social services commissioner cesar perales rejected charges by 
the legal aid society of illegal and substandard conditions at the 
martinique hotel in manhattan but a legal aid lawyer said perales 
was wrong and pledged a lawsuit 
to call a room thats 9by12 not a cubicle is no consolation 
to a family living in it said the lawyer steven banks 
state regulations require that rooms in which homeless 
families are placed contain private bathrooms banks said even 
the commissioner conceded today that these rooms do not have 
private bathrooms 
perales ordered an investigation after banks charged this week 
that as many as 80 rooms at the martinique had been subdivided into 
9by12foot cubicles and lacked sufficient furniture 
city officials and a hotel coowner said some tworoom suites 
used in the past by one large family had been split up for two 
smaller families and that bathrooms were shared legally perales 
said the same friday 
we observed no evidence of new construction or of rooms being 
divided into tiny cubicles and we observed no evidence of major 
infestations of roaches or rats 
while some suites were split with bathrooms shared each 
family has a private entrance perales said each bathroom can 
be locked on both sides to ensure total privacy 
banks said the issue was not new construction and he had not 
alleged rat or roach infestations but that families were being 
crammed into small rooms and forced to share bathrooms 
