<TEXT>
the nations displaced workers are not 
receiving adequate job search assistance training counseling or 
benefits a study group for senate republicans reported friday 
the report by a task force of the senate republican conference 
said that of the more than 1 million american workers displaced 
annually due to plant closings or layoffs more than onethird of 
them have extended periods of unemployment while some never return 
to the workforce 
of those who do return almost onehalf take pay cuts and more 
than onethird earn less than fourfifths of what they previously 
had earned according to the study group which was chaired by john 
h chafee ri 
the group recommended that congress enact a 980 million reagan 
administration proposal which would consolidate two current 
education and job training programs the job training partnership 
act and the trade adjustment assistance act 
the new worker adjustment program is designed to serve an 
estimated 700000 workers and would seek to eliminate costly 
duplication of effort it would also provide substantially greater 
emphasis on actual retraining 
the 69page report said that poor publicity a general lack of 
coordination among different federal assistance programs and a 
slow response rate when the programs have actually have been 
implemented have plagued the delivery and quality of assistance 
to displaced workers 
projections for the next 15 years it said indicate that 
millions of americans are not only illprepared for existing jobs 
but will have even more difficulty finding and holding jobs in the 
future unless the work force is retrained and continuously 
prepared for marketplace change 
the united states is faced with the creation of a growing 
underclass increasingly made up of former manufacturing and 
industrial workers without the skills to enter the work place 
the report said 
the gop conference is an organization made of all 46 republican 
senators 
