<DOCNO> AP880520-0222 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
house and senate negotiators reached tentative 
compromise friday on a new medicare prescription drug benefit that 
could clear the way for final votes on a catastrophic health 
insurance bill next week 
rep fortney h stark dcalif told reporters the drug issue 
was the most complicated item separating house and senate members 
of a conference committee 
asked when the committee would have a final compromise ready for 
submission to the house and senate start said i hope next 
week 
but stark noted that several other issues are outstanding 
including the precise way flat and slidingscale premiums will be 
imposed on the 31 million medicare beneficiaries to pay for 
additional benefits and whether participation in the expanded 
coverage will be mandatory or voluntary 
the tentative drug compromise being recommended by an 
eightmember working group to the full conference committee calls 
for the new benefit to be phased in starting jan 1 1991 
medicare does not now cover any outpatient drugs except for a 
handful of particularly costly medications such as antirejection 
drugs for transplant recipients 
under the recommended compromise medicare would pay half the 
cost of prescriptions in 1991 after a 600 deductible is met 
medicare would pay 60 percent of drug costs the following year 
and 80 percent in subsequent years but still only on that portion 
that exceeds 600 a year 
the premiums charged beneficiaries to cover the new benefit 
would be indexed each year to cover the cost of the program which 
is expected to grow each year 
the initial level of those premiums and details of the indexing 
are to be worked out in subsequent negotiations of the full 
conference committee 
the full conference also has to resolve several other albeit 
less thorny differences 
however there is broad support for the legislation and 
negotiators expressed confidence at their first public meeting 
earlier this month that a compromise would be reached quickly 
both bills passed their respective houses by overwhelming 
margins and are patterned after the basic framework proposed by 
president reagan 
neither measure makes provisions for longterm nursing home care 
under medicare but would shield medicare beneficiaries against 
financially crippling outofpocket doctor and hospital bills 
while the cap on how much beneficiaries would have to pay is one 
of the issues still to be resolved it is expected to be between 
1043 the latest house offer and 1370 the latest senate 
offer medicare would pick up all hospital and physician costs for 
a beneficiary after the cap is met in a given year 
medicare now pays full costs of only 60 days of a hospital stay 
in a given year minus a firstday deductible and pays only 80 
percent of doctor bills no matter how high they range 
on the cost side the major disagreement is how to distribute 
the additional premium medicare enrollees will have to pay 
particularly the socalled supplemental premium that is tantamount 
to an income tax surcharge for the estimated 60 percent of retirees 
who would be subject to it 
each beneficiary will have to pay a flat monthly premium for the 
catastrophic coverage but about 40 percent do not have enough 
income to make them also subject to the slidingscale supplemental 
premium that will be based on their ability to pay and be collected 
through the income tax system 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

