<TEXT>
singapore plans to convert its largely 
ceremonial presidency into an elected post with executive powers 
and lee kuan yew seems likely to seek that role after he retires as 
prime minister 
confirmation that an elected president is in the works was made 
in parliament thursday 
legislation described as only a very preliminary draft which 
needs considerable revision and improvements has been prepared 
said phua bah lee a senior parliamentary secretary 
phuas brief statement was a written reply to a question 
submited by chaim see tong the only opposition member of 
parliament it ended four years of speculation that basic changes 
were planned in the way this bustling island republic is governed 
the president is now named by parliament to a fouryear term 
wee kim wee 72 a former diplomat and journalist has been 
president since 1985 
in his national day address in 1984 lee said the constitution 
might be changed to prevent any future government from squandering 
singapores ample reserves he said an elected president with veto 
power over access to these assets might be the answer 
lee has for years said he would like to follow the example of 
many us corporate leaders and step down at 65 he reaches that 
age on sept 16 
goh chok tong 46 who was named first deputy prime minister 
after the 1984 elections is positioned to succeed lee the prime 
ministers eldest son trade and industry minister lee hsien loong 
36 is also regarded as eventual prime ministerial material a 
retired army general he entered politics less than four years ago 
observers here say the elder lee would be a natural candidate 
for the presidential post 
a cambridgeeducated lawyer lee became prime minister in 1959 
on a wave of anticolonialism and with the help of communists whom 
he later purged but steady economic growth has endeared lee to a 
population of 26 million that enjoys one of the highest living 
standards in asia 
