action by five kwandebele women were ordered to pay costs about 50 
women wearing traditional colorful blankets attended fridays 
session at pretoria supreme court 
kwandebele is the only of south africas 10 black homelands 
where women have not been allowed to vote 
the judge also said the 1984 elections for 16 legislative seats 
were null and void one of the 16 seats was captured by majozi 
mahlangu who later was elected chief minister of the homeland by 
the assembly of the 77 seats in the assembly 61 are appointed 
it was not immediately clear how or when the empty seats will be 
filled and whether mahlangu will be allowed to remain chief 
minister 
kwandebele is an impoverished area the size of luxembourg with 
almost no resources or infrastructure about 400000 people live in 
the territory northeast of pretoria and many workers spend up to 
eight hours a day commuting to jobs in white areas 
the homeland currently has selfgoverning status but is 
considering opting for independence as four homelands already have 
done kwandebele authorities have been accused of harsh treatment 
toward dissidents who oppose independence 
nic de villiers of the pretoria legal resource center said the 
police play an overtly political role in the homeland and often 
mistreat activists 
not only does the tone of the police leadership permit 
assaults it positively encourages them de villiers said at a 
recent conference organized by lawyers for human rights 
the south african government said it created the homelands so 
that each major black tribe could exercise selfgovernment on its 
own territory critics of the system say it is part of the 
governments effort to splinter the black majority so that 
whiteminority rule can more easily be maintained 
