japan to offer new proposals 
smith the deputy us trade representative was in japan to 
attend the threeday pacific economic cooperation conference which 
ended friday he met for unofficial talks with officials at the 
ministry of agriculture forestry and fisheries thursday 
on friday he told a news conference at the us embassy the 
us is prepared to listen but we feel the japanese must show more 
flexibility in their position it is not up to the united 
states to make more proposals but up to japan 
were over here and theyre over there he said adding that 
as a negotiator he saw no reason for optimism yet 
smith said japans semigovernmental livestock industry 
promotion corp which controls imports of beef interferes in 
the market and should stay out of our business 
the corporation charges a 50 percent tax on imported beef before 
it is sold to wholesalers 
he reiterated the us position against surcharges on beef 
imports saying such surcharges hurt foreign exporters and violate 
the general agreement on tariffs and trade a genevabased forum 
for international trade disputes 
smith said that unlike tariffs surcharges are unilateral 
measures which involve no swapping with trading partners and 
upset the balance set in tariff negotiations 
he said surcharges fluctuate to stabilize prices and add an 
element of uncertainty to exporters while tariffs are fixed and 
transparent 
in response to a reporters question smith also said an 
increase in japans tariffs would seem exceedingly strange 
since tariffs are a transitional measure to cushion producers 
during structural changes 
instead smith suggested that japan establish a domestic income 
maintenance system that would not burden foreign exporters 
though both sides have expressed a desire to settle the dispute 
between themselves the united states has brought the issue before 
gatt and will keep pursuing gatt action until and unless there is 
a bilateral decision smith said 
an earlier usjapanese agreement setting quotas on us beef 
and citrus exports to japan expired in march talks to set a new 
timetable for market liberalization broke down and washington took 
its case to gatt on may 4 
australia another major exporter of beef to japan has also 
filed a complaint with the international body 
