<TEXT>
a federal judge on friday temporarily 
blocked reagan administration plans to start random drug testing of 
all 13000 federal prison workers saying the testing of 
lawabiding employees posed constitutional problems 
us district judge stanley weigel issued a temporary 
restraining order sought by a labor union against the bureau of 
prisons one of the first federal agencies scheduled to begin drug 
testing under president reagans september 1986 executive order 
the program would force lawabiding employees of the bureau of 
prisons to submit to testing even though not suspected of any 
wrongdoing negligence or dereliction of duty weigel said in his 
order 
the 750000member american federation of government employees 
the largest union representing federal workers also has challenged 
reagans entire drug testing program covering 345000 employees in 
40 agencies in a separate lawsuit 
the union chose the federal court in san francisco for both 
suits because of favorable precedents from the 9th us circuit 
court of appeals which has ruled against postaccident testing of 
railroad workers 
the supreme court may resolve the issue in a case scheduled for 
argument this fall involving the testing of applicants for jobs and 
promotions in the customs service 
weigels order blocks testing of prison workers which had been 
set to start monday until at least next thursday when a hearing 
is scheduled on a longerlasting preliminary injunction the 
injunction if granted could be appealed to higher courts 
weigel pressed a government lawyer apparently without success 
to bypass the preliminary injunction hearing and allow the ban to 
stay in effect until a fullscale trial of the lawsuit june 16 
i dont think the worlds going to come to an end because the 
program is delayed until a full careful consideration the judge 
said 
but justice department lawyer richard lepley said the government 
was unwilling to let the temporary ban which cannot be appealed 
stay in effect longer than the 20day legal limit for restraining 
orders 
at a hearing thursday lepley said the bureau of prisons had 
concluded that even a few days delay in testing would cause a 
great chance of serious injury even death both weigel and a 
union lawyer questioned that claim 
under reagans 1986 order federal agencies are to conduct 
random urinalysis testing of employees in sensitive jobs and 
also test applicants for new jobs and promotions workers involved 
in accidents and supervisors workers who fail the tests can be 
fired if they decline rehabilitation and lesser discipline 
the bureau of prisons has declared that all its employees hold 
sensitive jobs and therefore are subject to random testing 
with 5 to 10 percent of the staff tested each year 
the afge suit contends the program violates constitutional 
standards for unreasonable searches by allowing testing without 
individual suspicion of drug use the suit also claims violations 
of federal laws forbidding discrimination against the handicapped 
and requiring employee discipline to be related to job performance 
in his order weigel said supreme court and appellate rulings 
cast serious doubt upon the constitutionality and lawfulness of 
the program 
the judge said his order does not prohibit testing of any prison 
employee based on a reasonable suspicion of drug use that impairs 
job performance that is the standard the government has been 
following since 1985 lepley said 
</TEXT>
