the us labor department has asked the justice 
department to consider criminal prosecution of unocal corp and its 
executives for a 1984 refinery explosion in south suburban lemont 
that killed 17 people 
the labor department made its request thursday following a 
finding by an administrative judge that unocal then called union 
oil co violated federal health and safety regulations overseen by 
the ocupational safety and health administration 
unocal is appealing osha citations and the administrative 
finding to the us court of appeals in chicago 
while it does the company faces the prospect that it and 
individual employees could be found in criminal violation of 
federal safety regulations 
osha has the right to seek criminal prosecution for such 
violations but rarely has done so during the reagan 
administration according to the national safe workplace institute 
osha found that unocal violations included inadequate 
inspections for cracks in a pressure tank that exploded as well as 
poor training for its fire brigade 
in addition to the 17 killed the july 23 1984 explosion 
injured 21 others 
after reviewing government and company claims osha 
administrative judge rm child concluded that the company failed 
to adequately inspect for the presence of cracks in pressure 
vessels which exposed employees to increased likelihood of fire or 
explosion 
child also found that the company failed to use inspection 
techniques to determine the presence or absence of cracks and that 
this was a willful failure 
he said the company willfully failed to provide 
fireprotective clothing to persons required to handle fires and 
willfully failed to provide adequate firefighting and education 
to its shift fire brigade 
child rejected one alleged violation and reduced the original 
fine levied against unocal to 22000 from 31000 
officials of los angelesbased unocal declined to comment 
pending a review of the osha action 
